HEADWORD: Flyte
<hw>Flyte</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>fl⟦imac⟧t</ets>. See <er>Flite</er>.]</ety>
<def>Strife; dispute; abusive or upbraiding talk, as in fliting;
wrangling.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Scot. & Prov. Eng.]</mark></p>

<p><q>The bird of Pallas has also a good ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>flyte</qex>⟦rdquo⟧
on the moral side . . . in his suggestion that the principal effect of
the nightingale's song is to make women false to their husbands.</q>
<rj><qau>Saintsbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

